<p>And the answer is, yup, and it would be fairly easy with existing technology. &nbsp;Just sending up a probe to hover near an existing asteroid that regularly comes within the zone of near miss orbits would allow a slight gravitational tug to pull it onto the right course, and then, Tada! &nbsp;Not even cockroaches and amoebas to start over with! &nbsp;</p>
<p>You can now imagine the president asking Dr. Strangelove, "Not even the monkeys?"</p>
<p>Of course, nobody but a madman would think of doing something like this. &nbsp;But they might think of targeting the planet with smaller asteroids. &nbsp;It might even be cheaper than developing a nuclear program and with fewer international controls. &nbsp;Who could complain if some country wants to send scientific space probes to see the asteroids? &nbsp;Merely developing the technology for STUDYING the asteroid belt on a regular basis would make such a country more dangerous to the survival of the species than being a member of the nuke club, and not somebody to be trifled with.</p>

