  <div class="ct">
  
<p>are chaotic, as illustrated by a classic physics conundrum called the three body problem and we know planets move all over the place in other solar systems. We see them in strange places where they were unlikely to form sometimes. How exactly this happens is a topic of intense research and debate among planetary astronomers right now.</p>
<p>Decay is a slightly different deal, the earth's atmosphere actually extends for a thousand or more miles into space but it's incredibly tenuous. It's just thick enough that, over time, it can slow an object down that's orbiting inside that super thin envelope, which causes the object to drop in its orbit, where the atmosphere is ever so slightly thicker and slows it down ever so slightly faster, etc, and eventually it comes streaking in like skylab.</p>

